data.content:
## What happened

C# 14 introduces new `Span<T>` / `ReadOnlySpan<T>` conversions. Overload resolution now prefers `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(this ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` over `Enumerable.Contains<T>(this IEnumerable<T>, T)` when called on an array. Expression trees **cannot represent** span-based method calls, so this throws at runtime.

## How to fix

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<T>` so the compiler binds to `Enumerable.Contains`:

```csharp
// Option 1: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

The same issue affects `array.Reverse()` (now resolves to the in-place `Span` version). Use `Enumerable.Reverse(array)` in those cases too.
